When the customer has a post-function to copy a value from a custom field of an issue to another custom field on another issue if the field is not enabled on the new issue the following error will be displayed:
{code}
"We can't create this issue for you right now, it could be due to unsupported content you've entered into one or more of the issue fields. If this situation persists, contact your administrator as they'll be able to access more specific information in the log file."
{code}

It would be nice to have more information about the error itself on the error to help fix the issue without having to engage support to request the logs.

h3. Problem Description

Based on the previous issue which was described on the ticket here. An update is needed to be made in the document [here.|https://confluence.atlassian.com/jirasoftwarecloud/advanced-searching-operators-reference-764478341.html#Advancedsearching-operatorsreference-DOES_NOT_CONTAINDOESNOTCONTAIN:!~]This should be an expected clause but it has not been updated in the document. Please refer the bug JRACLOUD-65876 where the following was mentioned by the reviewing developer

{quote}
This is the expected behaviour, I will notify our tech writers to see if there is any piece of documentation where we could highlight this to avoid confusion in the future.
{quote}

h3. Summary

When Using the JQL:
{code:java}
comment !~ "Text"
{code}
{color:#f6c342}If an issue has more than one (>1) comment the "DOES NOT CONTAIN: !~" JQL is ignored results that contain the "Text" show up in search result{color}
h3. Expected Results

The highlighted line above should show in the documentation, as this has been mentioned by dev team in the related bug ticket here.
h3. Actual Results

The bug ticket mentioned clause is not visible in the documentation.

According to analytics, the evaluators trying to create a project with sample data experience an internal error {color:#ff0000}5.7%{color} of the time.

On a 3 weeks period in November 2017, the event {color:#ff0000}jira.project.templates.dialog.create.demo.failure{color} was emitted on 33 instances out of our filtered 552 which tried to create a sample project.

If true, this is slightly serious as it can stall an evaluation, and the occurence rate is not negligible.

Period: {color:#222222}]20171106-20171124[{color}

{color:#222222}Filter: Jira+Confluence bundle, Jira being primary intent, during evaluation.{color}

It would be great to be able to load the `all.js` library using the Fetch API.

That would allow us to mock the request on our test and CI environments with far more ease than the current way (at least for static add-ons).

Since the library is already 100% public, I see no downsides on allowing CORS for this resource alone, but it would allow us to do the following.
{code:java}
fetch(scriptUrl).then((response) => {
  let script = document.createElement('script')
  script.type = 'text/javascript'
  script.text = response.body
  document.getElementsByTagName('head')[0].appendChild(script)
}) 
{code}
Which allows for a very simple way of mocking the library request on test environments.

